Apply the same ticks > 0 guard that was added for col 11 to the existing cols 6–8 block:

if validPID && ticks > 0 {
    row[6] = nullString(formatCPUTime(curCPU.Utime+curCPU.Stime, ticks))
    row[7] = nullString(formatCPUTime(curCPU.Utime, ticks))
    row[8] = nullString(formatCPUTime(curCPU.Stime, ticks))
} else if validPID {
    row[6] = nullString("0:00:00")
    row[7] = nullString("0:00:00")
    row[8] = nullString("0:00:00")
} else {
    row[6] = nullString("0")
    ...
}

Alternatively, add a ticks > 0 check inside formatCPUTime itself and return "0:00:00" on zero ticks to enforce the contract at the function boundary.

Sanitize or truncate the line content before embedding in error messages. A simple approach: replace non-printable bytes, or limit the embedded content to a fixed width. For example:

const maxLineInErr = 80
snippet := line
if len(snippet) > maxLineInErr {
    snippet = snippet[:maxLineInErr] + "..."
}
return stat, fmt.Errorf("%s bad content: missing comm boundary in %q", statfile, snippet)

Using %q (Go's quoted-string verb) automatically escapes non-printable bytes, which is the safest option.
